narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Strengthened knowledge of functions, derivatives, and differential calculus.
This was my first Calculus class, and I felt that I learned a lot. At the end of the class I had a great understanding of the content.
Introductory calculus and review of algebra skills.

The basics of calculus! No frills! If you want to go deeper into the material, there's always that possibility (Khan Academy, reading the textbook chapters in depth, office hours), but you can just as easily stick to the surface (daily homeworks, weekly PSETs, lectures) and do very well.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Strengths: Well taught, plenty of opportunities for interaction with peers and ULAs at workshop and office hours. The course content was presented at a reasonable pace as opposed to MATH 112 which is daunting and a somewhat steep curve for someone who doesn't have any experience in calculus.

The strengths of this class are the small canvas assignments due before class. These really helped me grasp basic content. I really think that doing more practice problems with answers would have helped me though.
The workshops are repetitive and unnecessary. The ULA system is very strong for office hours, though.

This course is a relatively easy (re)entry into calculus. For me, it was a re-entry (it had been several years)--which gave me a small advantage--and I think MATH 110 and Kien did a great job making this course understandable, collaborative, and in terms of time investment and difficulty/exams, very reasonable.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, especially if you want a reasonably paced calculus course.
I would recommend this class to any students who have not taken calculus previously. I think it was a great basic class!
Yes. It is structured very well to facilitate learning for students who may have struggled previously with math.
Yes, I would, either to build a foundation in calculus, excavate forgotten math from high school, or as I did, choose a QR credit that asks relatively little of you.
